{"author":{"id":"8e1777f58c0cfe5478428be8f9fcbfe90d25e44689578335da8fc2246fe0915a"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1452901334,"nonce":"qaKCYrQ3qgligdB5UGdCns7oXfE=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDE3MjEyNzI5NQ==","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/522#issuecomment-172127295"},"message":"Short update from my side: \n\nWe have a work in progress `travis` [branch](https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/tree/travis).\nThis works with conda dependencies that we have added to bioconda and planemo that installs these dependencies and tests the tools. Thanks @jmchilton for fixing planemo and the bioconda community for the fruitful discussions.\n\nThere is still some work to do, but I feel ready to show what we have so far to gather a little bit of feedback.\nThere is a [tool test blacklist](https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/blob/travis/.tt_blacklist) and we start with all tools blacklisted. Packages and data_managers are blacklisted as well but in the helper python script as we can not test them properly.\n\nIf we want to get a tool under testing we just need to remove it from the blacklist and the correct dependency needs to be in conda.\n\nThe idea is to require, at time of merging the branch, a conda dependency for every tool, next to a tool_dependency (until GCC) and every new tools needs to pass these tests.\n\nI would like to propose a new codefest if you all agree and in which the IUC core team and others create conda recipes for our tools and get tools under testing with the aim to empty the blacklist.\n\nPlease let me know what you think!\n\n@mvdbeek improving documentation is easy. Just let me know what can be improved and I will do so. Also we are in discussion with bioconda to improve sustainability and I have created an IUC channel that we can use for all stuff that does not fit in bioconda. \n\nP.S. How to get your tool under testing?\nCreate a patch like [this](https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/commit/a603c8121a7da6dd5c97c36237a3e1c86e906e70) and target it against the `travis` branch.","files":null}]}